# Adding a New Policy

This guide explains how to add a new policy to the Justice Digital Data and Science Policy Hub using GitHub's web interface. **You don't need any special software - just a web browser!**

---

## Prerequisites

- GitHub account with access to the repository
- Your policy content ready to add
- Understanding of the policy details (owner, sponsor, dates, etc.)

---

## Step 1: Go to GitHub

1. Open your web browser
2. Go to [https://github.com/ministryofjustice/Justice-Digital-Data-and-Science-Policy-Hub](https://github.com/ministryofjustice/Justice-Digital-Data-and-Science-Policy-Hub)
3. You should see the repository home page

---

## Step 2: Navigate to the Policies Folder

1. Click on the **Code** tab (near the top of the page)
2. Look for the folder structure - you'll see folders like `source/`, `config/`, etc.
3. Click on the `source/` folder
4. Click on the `policies/` folder inside
5. You'll now see the existing policy files

---

## Step 3: Create a New File

1. In the `policies/` folder, click the **Add file** button (top right)
2. Select **Create new file** from the dropdown menu

---

## Step 4: Name Your Policy File

In the filename field at the top, enter your policy name using this format:

**Format:** `policy-name.html.md.erb`

**Rules:**
- Use lowercase letters only
- Use hyphens (-) instead of spaces
- Always end with `.html.md.erb`

**Examples:**
- `data-protection-policy.html.md.erb`
- `information-security-policy.html.md.erb`
- `accessibility-policy.html.md.erb`

---

## Step 5: Copy and Fill in the Template

Copy this entire template and paste it into the file:

```
---
title: [Policy Name]
weight: [50]
owner_slack: "#digital-compliance-team"
last_reviewed_on: 2026-06-03
review_in: 6 months
---

# [Policy Name]

## [Policy Name]

**Classification:** OFFICIAL

### Policy Details

| Field | Details |
|-------|---------|
| **Policy Identifier** | [Add policy identifier, e.g., JDDS-POL02] |
| **Policy Owner** | [Add policy owner name] |
| **Policy Sponsor** | [Add policy sponsor name] |
| **Date Created** | [Add date in DD/MM/YYYY format] |
| **Date Last Reviewed** | [Add date in DD/MM/YYYY format] |
| **Date of Next Review** | [Add date in DD/MM/YYYY format] |
| **Expiry** | When rescinded or replaced |
| **Version** | [Add version number, e.g., 1.0] |

---

## Purpose

[Write 2-3 sentences explaining why this policy exists and what it aims to achieve. Explain how it supports the organisation's objectives.]

---

## Scope

[Explain what the policy applies to. Include details about which departments, processes, and people it covers. Also mention what is NOT included.]

---

## Policy Statements

The following mandatory principles, standards and rules must be followed:

### Principles

1. [Add first principle]
2. [Add second principle]
3. [Add additional principles as needed]

---

## Roles and Responsibilities

| Role/Team | Responsibilities |
|-----------|-----------------|
| [Role Name] | [What they are responsible for] |
| [Another Role] | [Their responsibilities] |

### Policy Reviewers

[Name of team/people] will be responsible for reviewing this policy annually, and any ad hoc reviews, to ensure it remains accurate and fit for purpose.

---

## Monitoring and Compliance

[Explain how compliance will be monitored, measured and reported. Include who is responsible for monitoring.]

---

## Exceptions

Any deviations from this policy must be formally approved by the Senior Responsible Owner (SRO). Applications to deviate from the policy must be documented and subject to risk assessment.

---

## Breach of Policy

Policy must be adhered to, and any breaches may result in steps being taken under the MoJ Performance Management Policy.

[Add details about specific consequences of non-compliance if relevant to this policy.]

---

## Related Policies and Guidance

The following policies and guidance support this policy:

- [Link text](https://example.gov.uk)
- [Another link](https://example.gov.uk)

---

## Review and Update

This policy must be reviewed on an annual basis, or sooner where there are significant changes to regulatory requirements or organisational strategy.

Reviews must be conducted by the policy reviewers and approved by the Policy Owner prior to publication.
```

---

## Step 6: Replace the Template Text

Now go through the template and replace all the text in square brackets `[...]` with your actual information:

| Replace This | With Your Information |
|--------------|----------------------|
| `[Policy Name]` | The name of your policy (e.g., "Data Protection Policy") |
| `[50]` | A weight number (see Weight Guidance below) |
| `"#digital-compliance-team"` | Leave as-is unless you have a different Slack channel |
| `2026-06-03` | Today's date in YYYY-MM-DD format (e.g., 2026-06-03) |
| `6 months` | How often the policy should be reviewed (e.g., `6 months`, `1 year`) |
| `[JDDS-POL02]` | Your policy identifier number |
| `[Add policy owner name]` | The person responsible for the policy |
| `[Add policy sponsor name]` | The senior leader who backs the policy |
| `[DD/MM/YYYY]` | Dates in this format: 01/06/2026 |
| Each section content | Your policy text for that section |

### Weight Guidance

The weight determines where your policy appears in the list:
- **10** = Policy Template
- **20** = Service Standards Policy  
- **50+** = New policies (use 50, 60, 70, etc.)

Lower numbers appear higher in the list.

---

## Step 7: Preview Your File

As you type, GitHub shows a preview. Look for:
- Spelling mistakes
- Proper table formatting (make sure `|` characters are correct)
- All square brackets `[...]` have been filled in

---

## Step 8: Save Your Draft (Commit)

1. Scroll down to the bottom of the page
2. You'll see the **Commit new file** section
3. In the commit message field, write a brief description:
   ```
   Add Data Protection Policy
   ```
4. Make sure **Create a new branch for this commit and start a pull request** is selected
5. Click **Commit new file**

---

## Step 9: Create a Pull Request

A pull request page will appear. This is where you ask the team to review your policy before it's published.

1. The title field already has your commit message - that's fine
2. In the description, add any helpful notes for reviewers:
   ```
   This is a new data protection policy following the MoJ guidelines.
   Policy owner approval is pending.
   ```
3. Click **Create pull request**

---

## Step 10: Wait for Review

The admin team will now review your policy:

1. They may ask questions or request changes
2. You'll receive notifications in GitHub
3. You can respond to comments directly
4. Once approved, they'll merge your policy
5. Your policy will automatically appear on the website!

---

## Tips for Writing Your Policy

### Keep it Clear
- Use short, simple sentences
- Avoid jargon (explain technical terms if you must use them)
- Use bullet points for lists
- Use plain language

### Formatting
- **Bold text**: Wrap in `**text**`
- *Italic text*: Wrap in `*text*`
- [Links](https://example.com): Use `[Text](URL)`

### Tables

Tables are easy in GitHub. Use this format:

```
| Column 1 | Column 2 |
|----------|----------|
| Your data | More data |
| Row 2 | Data |
```

### Dates

Always use this format: `DD/MM/YYYY`

Examples:
- 01/06/2026 ✓
- 1/6/2026 ✗
- 06/01/2026 ✗

